{
  "_comment": "Layer 7 demo — write-back vs write-through. Two caches sharing the same write-heavy trace: WT (write-through) and WB (write-back). The trace writes to address 0 eight times in a row, then reads it. With write-through, every CPU write produces a RAM write (MEM_WE pulses 8 times). With write-back, the writes stay in the cache (line marked dirty), and RAM stays untouched until a future eviction. Open the Pipeline panel CACHE (LIVE) section: hits/misses are identical for both, but only the WB cache reports stats.writebacks (visible by hovering Memory Inspector — D = dirty bit). Trace driver: PC counts 0..7, ROM emits the constant address 0 with WE asserted to make every step a write to addr 0 with the cycle index as data.",
